  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Source of Funds Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The most common reason for delays and rejections. Ireland requires clear, auditable proof of how you acquired your €2M+ net worth and the specific investment funds. "I sold my business" isn't enough—you need sale contracts, bank transfers, tax payments, and potentially third-party verification. Start gathering documentation months in advance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Transferring Investment Funds Before Approval</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">A critical error. The IIP requires you to receive approval before completing your investment. If you transfer €1M to an Irish company before approval and your application is rejected, you may have difficulty recovering your funds. Wait for official approval letter.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing the Wrong Investment Vehicle</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Each investment route has different risk-return profiles and requirements. Enterprise investments require due diligence on the business. Fund investments require approved fund selection. Endowments are non-refundable. REIT investments require €2M instead of €1M. Consult professionals before committing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting the Annual Visit Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While Ireland has minimal residency requirements, you must visit Ireland at least once per calendar year to maintain your status. Failure to do so can jeopardize your residence permit renewal. Keep records of your visits (boarding passes, hotel receipts).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Inadequate Health Insurance for Dependents</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Your insurance must cover all family members included in your IIP application—spouse and children under 24. Policies that only cover the main applicant will not satisfy requirements. Ensure your coverage explicitly names all dependents and meets Irish requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Ireland -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Ireland</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Ireland operates a mixed public-private healthcare system. The public Health Service Executive (HSE) provides care to all ordinary residents, while private healthcare offers faster access and more amenities. As an IIP investor with required private insurance, you'll have access to Ireland's excellent private healthcare sector.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Understanding the Irish System</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Private Healthcare (Your Primary Access)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ Private hospitals in Dublin, Cork, Galway</li>
          <li>✓ Choice of consultant specialists</li>
          <li>✓ Minimal waiting times</li>
          <li>✓ Private rooms and superior amenities</li>
          <li>✓ Access to latest treatments and technology</li>
          <li>✓ GP consultations (€50-70 private)</li>
          <li>✓ Dental and vision typically separate</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Public HSE System (After Residency)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Free public hospital treatment</li>
          <li>• GP Visit Card or Medical Card if eligible</li>
          <li>• A&E access (€100 charge, waived with referral)</li>
          <li>• Longer waiting times for elective procedures</li>
          <li>• Means-tested eligibility for full coverage</li>
          <li>• Drug Payment Scheme caps costs at €80/month</li>
          <li>• Quality care but potential delays</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Key Hospitals and Facilities</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Dublin</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Beacon Hospital, Blackrock Clinic, Mater Private Hospital, Hermitage Medical Clinic. World-class facilities with international patient services. Most specialists based in Dublin.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Cork</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Bon Secours Hospital Cork, Mater Private Cork. Strong regional healthcare with good specialist coverage. Growing medical tourism destination.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Galway</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Bon Secours Hospital Galway, Galway Clinic. Good private facilities serving the west of Ireland. Some specialist care may require Dublin travel.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GPs:</strong> Register with a local GP (General Practitioner). Consultations typically €50-70 for private patients.</li>
      <li><strong>Specialists:</strong> Usually need GP referral, or your insurance may allow direct specialist access.</li>
      <li><strong>Emergencies:</strong> Call 999 or 112. A&E departments in all major hospitals. €100 charge without GP referral.</li>
      <li><strong>Pharmacies:</strong> Widely available. Many medications require prescription.</li>
      <li><strong>Dental:</strong> Separate from medical insurance. Private dental widely available.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Healthcare quality:</strong> Ireland's healthcare system ranks well internationally, particularly for cancer care, cardiac care, and medical research. Dublin hospitals are affiliated with major medical schools and attract top specialists. Private patients can expect care comparable to other developed nations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the Ireland Immigrant Investor Programme still open?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The IIP was suspended in February 2024 and is not currently accepting new applications. The Irish government has not announced a reopening date. Monitor official announcements from Immigration Service Delivery for updates. Consider alternative EU programmes like Portugal's Golden Visa in the meantime.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum investment for the Ireland investor visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          When active, the lowest entry point was €500,000 through the endowment (donation) route, or €400,000 per person for group donations of 5+ investors. Enterprise and fund investments required €1,000,000, while REIT investments required €2,000,000. All routes required proof of €2,000,000 minimum net worth.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to live in Ireland with the IIP?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. One of the IIP's main attractions was the minimal residency requirement—just one visit to Ireland per calendar year. You could maintain residency while living primarily elsewhere. However, for citizenship (after 5 years), you must have 1 year of continuous residence immediately before applying.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is private health insurance really mandatory?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Private health insurance covering you and your dependents in Ireland is a mandatory condition of the IIP. You must provide proof of insurance with your application and maintain coverage throughout your residence. The public HSE system is not accepted as a substitute for initial applicants.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family be included in the application?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your spouse and children under 24 years old can be included as dependents in your IIP application. Each dependent must have health insurance and will receive their own Irish Residence Permit. Adult children over 24 must apply separately or through their own qualifying investment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get Irish citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 5 years of legal residence in Ireland, you can apply for citizenship through naturalization. Requirements include: 1 year of continuous residence immediately before application, good character, and intention to continue residing in Ireland. No language test is required. Irish citizenship grants an EU passport.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
